							A bizarre, frustrating evening unfolded in front of a capacity crowd at the Glenn Miller Ballroom Wednesday night as Utah writer Terry Tempest Williams was presented with the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.centerwest.org" title="Center of the American West">Center of the American West</a> Wallace Stegner Award for 2005.  Hundreds packed the room for the event, which honors â€œan individual who has made a sustained contribution to the cultural identity of the West.â€? Western scholars Patricia Nelson Limerick and Charles Wilkinson introduced Williams and then tried to spark a meaningful conversation with her, but it was clear from the beginning that Williams wasnâ€™t in the proper emotional state to be on stage in front of a crowd. Williams repeatedly broke down in tears, trailed off in the middle of sentences (confessing several times, â€œI just lost my train of thoughtâ€?) and experienced evident difficulty at understanding questions put to her (she often asked that the questions be repeated several times). <br />
<br />
At first it wasnâ€™t apparent why Williams was having such difficultyâ€”she seemed overcome with gratitude at the massive turnout, and even took several photographs of the crowd from the stage.  After rambling for a few inaudible minutes in response to Limerickâ€™s question about why she had become a writer, Williams said, â€œIâ€™m a mess.  This is really difficult.  Iâ€™m not sitting here from a place of strength.  My brother passed away in January of Lymphoma. This year was one of deep contemplation and struggle.  I also just returned home from Rwanda. When the invitation came to travel to Rwanda, I wasnâ€™t in a good place to make the trip.  But we donâ€™t choose where weâ€™re sent.  Thatâ€™s a spiritual belief of mine.â€?  As was typical of the confusing presentation, Williams never clarified who had invited her to Rwanda or what exactly she was doing there.<br />
<br />
During her introduction, Limerick noted that her recent weight loss was due to the â€œfar too early death of my husband.â€? Williams and Limerick are old friends, and they spent much of the evening swapping tales about past that came across as inside jokes and shared memories that were inaccessible (and often inaudible) to the crowd. It felt very much like two grieving women were conducting a private conversation in front of a huge audience, and it was painful to watch.  The normally very entertaining and polished presenter Limerick tried to steer the conversation back around several times toward topics relevant to the West, to Wallace Stegner, and to Williamsâ€™ career as an activist writer, but Williams couldnâ€™t focus. To her credit, she realized that the presentation was alienating and apologized: â€œThis was so indulgent tonight.  I thank you for your patience.  The worst thing you can do is bore an audience, and Iâ€™m sorry if Iâ€™ve done that.â€?<br />
<br />
Although Williams gradually became more audible, she never recovered from her incoherence. When one audience member asked her what she was working on currently, she said, â€œI donâ€™t know.  But Iâ€™m thinking a lot about prairie dogs, and I think thatâ€™s why I like Boulder, because youâ€™ve been thinking about prairie dogs for a long time, because they have something to teach us about community.â€?  She watched a prairie dog colony for fourteen hours a day over a recent two-week period.  She described behavior she interpreted as prairie dog prayer.  â€œI fell in love with this one prairie dog who would stand at the edge of her burrow in the evening and face the setting sun and put her paws together and stand in that posture for 30 minutes.  In the morning sheâ€™d do the same thing, facing to the east toward the rising sun.â€? She concluded her loopy reflections by stating, â€œI went to Rwanda and learned about the genocide there, and realized that there has been a similar genocide of prairie dogs in this country.â€?  I love prairie dogs as much as the next guy (see http://www.newwest.net/index.php/main/article/2681/), but equating the killing of prairie dogs with the torture and murders of tens of thousands of human beings in Rwanda is morally indefensible. If Rush Limbaugh really did call Williams â€œa left-wing radical environmental wackoâ€? as she claimed, itâ€™s hard to blame him if she goes around making statements like this.<br />
<br />
Last nightâ€™s Wallace Stegner Award was an unfortunate, wasted opportunity.  Terry Tempest Williams was in no state to make a public presentation, and the people at the Center of the American West should have realized this and had the kindness to postpone or shorten the event rather than putting Williams and the audience through a pointless evening.  In addition to fans of Williamsâ€™ work, the audience was filled with college students who were clearly required to attend by their professors.  The teenage boys sitting behind me kept up a running commentary and laugh track that was far more incisive than anything I heard from the stage.  The shame is that after seeing such a woeful presentation, boys like those will never willingly pick up a Terry Tempest Williams book or attend another literary event, which would seem to defeat the purpose of honoring Williams in this way.<br />

